We take the Laplace transform of the equation:

\begin{align*}\mathcal{L}(y'' - 2y' + y) = \mathcal{L}(g(t))\end{align*}

\begin{align*}\underbrace{s^2 Y(s) - s y(0) - y'(0)}_{\mathcal{L}(y'')} - 2 \underbrace{(sY(s) - y(0))}_{\mathcal{L}(y')} + \underbrace{Y(s)}_{\mathcal{L}(y)} = \underbrace{\frac{e^{-s}}{s-1}}_{\mathcal{L}(g(t))}\end{align*}

\begin{align*}s^2 Y(s) - 0 - 1 - 2(s Y(s) - 0) + Y(s) = (s^2 - 2s + 1) Y(s) - 1 = \frac{e^{-s}}{s-1}\end{align*}

Since $\displaystyle s^2 - 2s + 1 = (s-1)^2$ we arrive at our final
answer

\begin{align*}Y(s) = \frac{e^{-s}}{(s-1)^3} + \frac{1}{(s-1)^2}\end{align*}
